Part I - Ford GoBike System¶

by Nonso Ukwuma¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area over a certain period. The dataset contains over 183k records and has details of each ride such as the gender of the rider, the year of birth, destination, duration of trip, user type etc.

Data Cleaning observations¶

I made the following observations from the dataset which will require cleaning.

  1. Drop null and NA values from the dataset.
  2. Convert the data type of the member_birth_year column from float to Int.
  3. Create a member_age column using the member_birth_year provided and limit the records to riders aged 100 or under.
  4. Remove 'Other' gender from the member_gender column and retain only records where the gender is male or female.
  5. Create a column for duration_hours from the duration_sec column.
  6. Remove columns that will not be needed for this analysis such as 'start_time', 'end_time','start_station_id', 'end_station_id', 'end_station_latitude', 'start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_longitude'.

Code¶

In [7]:
#drop null and empty rows

bikeshare.dropna(inplace=True)
In [8]:
#change the data type for the member_birth_year column to Int

bikeshare['member_birth_year'] = bikeshare['member_birth_year'].astype('str')
bikeshare['member_birth_year'] = bikeshare['member_birth_year'].str.split('.', expand = True).get(0).astype('int')
In [9]:
#create a member_age column from the member_birth_year column details and limit rider age to 100 yrs

from datetime import date

bikeshare['member_age'] = date.today().year - bikeshare['member_birth_year']

bikeshare = bikeshare[bikeshare['member_age'] <= 100]
In [10]:
#Remove 'Other' gender from the member_gender column and retain only records where the gender is male or female.

bikeshare = bikeshare[bikeshare['member_gender'] != 'Other']
In [11]:
#Create a column for duration_hours from the duration_sec column.

bikeshare['duration_hours'] = round(bikeshare['duration_sec']/3600, 2)
In [12]:
#drop columns that will not be required for the analysis.

dcols = ['start_station_id', 'end_station_id', 'end_station_latitude', 'start_station_latitude', 
         'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_longitude', 'start_time', 'end_time']
bikeshare.drop(dcols, axis=1, inplace=True)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset is made up of categorical variables such as (member gender, user type, start station name, bike share for all trips) and numerical variable such as (duration in seconds and minutes, member age, member birth year, bike id).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features I have taken interest in are the user type, member gender and bike share for all trips.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe that the member gender and member age features might help me investigate what dataset to gain more insight into the user type and bike share for all trips features.

#create a function to plot categorical univariate charts
def cplot(dat, ft):
    col = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(data=dat, x=dat[ft], color= col, order=dat[ft].value_counts().index);

Observations¶

  1. There were more subscribers (about 155k) than customers (about 17k) who used the bike share within the period.
  2. There were more male bike share users (about 135k) compared to female users (about 40k).
  3. The number of bike share users who use the service for all trips is very low (about 15k) compared to the about 155k who do not use the service for all trips.

Visualization¶

plt.xlabel('Duration (hrs)')
plt.xticks(np.arange(0, 1.2, 0.1))
plt.title('Distribution of Bike Share Trips Durations');

Observations¶

  1. Majority of the bike share users are middle aged people between the ages of 24 and 43.
  2. The age group that made the highest number of trips is between 28 and 32 years.
  3. The distribution is right skewed with majority of the riders being younger while there are a few outliers with ages 70-90 years also participating in the bike share program.
  4. The distribution for the duration of the bike trips is also right skewed with most of the trips lasting 0.3hrs (18 mins) or less while some trips lasted as long as 45 mins to 1hr plus.

  3. Montgomery St. BART station
  4. Powell St BART Station
  5. San Fransisco ferry building

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  1. The user type showed that both subscribers and walk-in customers use the bike share program though there were more subscribers than customer.
  2. The number of people that use the bike share program for all trips is just a small portion of the overall users.
  3. I had to calculate the age of the riders using their date of birth and also conveterd the duration of each ride which was originally captured in seconds to hours to make it easier to understand.
  4. In gettting the top 10 start and end locations, I had to limit the output of the data to the 10 with the highest frequency.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  1. The age distribution showed that some of the riders were 80, 90 and above and I would not expect people at this age bracket to be riding bikes. I limited the age bracket to 100 years max during cleaning.
  2. The member gender had 'Other' as a gender and the number of occurences was limited hence I removed it during cleaning.

#Generate the grouped data required for this investigation.
x2 = bikeshare.groupby('user_type').sum().sort_values(by='duration_hours').reset_index()
y2 = bikeshare.groupby('bike_share_for_all_trip').sum().sort_values(by='duration_hours').reset_index()
c2 = bikeshare.groupby('member_gender').sum().sort_values(by='duration_hours').reset_index()

#create plots with the grouped data
plt.figure(figsize = [20, 5])

plt.subplot(1,3,1)
plt.bar(x2.user_type, x2.duration_hours);
plt.ylabel('Duration (hrs)')
plt.xlabel('User Type')
plt.title('Trip Duration Covered by each User Type Segment')

plt.subplot(1,3,2)
plt.bar(y2.bike_share_for_all_trip, y2.duration_hours)
plt.ylabel('Duration (hrs)')
plt.xlabel('bike_share_for_all_trip')
plt.title('Trip Duration Covered by Users of Bike Share for all trips Segment')

plt.subplot(1,3,3)
plt.bar(c2.member_gender, c2.duration_hours)
plt.ylabel('Duration (hrs)')
plt.xlabel('Member Gender')
plt.title('Trip Duration Covered by each Member Gender Segment');

Observations¶

  1. Subscribers obviously spent more time on trips cumulatively than walk in customers.
  2. Male users accounted for about 69% of all the trips while females had about 31%
  3. About 90% of the trip duration was by users who do not use the bikeshae service for all trips.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  1. There were more male bikeshare users than female users.
  2. The average age of the bikeshare service users is 35 years while majority are between the ages of 30 to 40 years.
  3. There are more bikeshare service subscribers than walk in customers.
  4. Most of the bikeshare service users do not use it for all trips.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  1. The sum of the total number hours spent on trips by users who do not use the bikeshare service for all trips is very high at 90% which implies that only 10% of the users use the service for all trips. This is interesting considering that subscribers accounted for about 66% of the total trip duration.

Conclusions¶

  1. The bike share service has a lot of users who are either subscribers or walk in customer though the number of subscribers is higher than the walk in customers.
  2. The bike share services has more of male users compared to female users.
  3. Majority of the bike share users are middle aged people between the ages of 21 and 43.
  4. Though the about 90% of the bike share users are subscribers while very little account for walk in customers, just very few (10%) use the bike share servcie for all trips while 90% of the users which cuts accross subscribers and customers do not use the service for all trips.
  5. There are more males than females who do not use the service for all trips.
  6. Younger customers both male and female (under 30 years) use the bike share service for all trips while the majority of users who do not use the service for all trips are aged between 30-41 years.
